Name: Cor a 1
BioNames: Pathogenesis-related protein, PR-10, Bet v 1 family member
Allergenicity: Sera of 20 patients with seasonal allergic rhinitis or asthma in early spring were tested. All patients has sIgE to a tree pollen extract mixture (birch, alder, hazel) > 3.5 kU/L and to Bet v 1. Of those, 20/20 has IgE to rCor a 1.0302 in ELISA and immunoblot.
naSequence: Expression of Cor a 1.03 mRNA was detected in pollen and in low amounts in nuts by RT-PCR with isoallergen-specific primers. Protein expression in pollen was shown by tandem mass spectrometry (97% sequence coverage). The sequence used for expressing the recombinant protein was amplified from cDNA using primers based on the genomic sequence from Lucas et al. (PubMed: 33249676).

Name: Cor a 11
naSequence: Signal peptide: 1-47; mature protein: 48-448; The mature proteins contains two potential N-glycosylation sites (N85 and N301) of which only N301 is glycosylated. Glycosylation was shown to not significantly contribute to IgE binding of the allergen.

Name: Cor a 11
Allergenicity: 106 children with suspected hazelnut allergy were tested. All had a positive IgE (ImmunoCAP) with hazelnut extract. IgE to the recombinant full-length protein (ImmunoCAP) was positive in 69 sera (65%). Sera from 57 patients were also tested by ImmunoCAP for IgE to the recombinant mature vicilin (lacking the N-terminal alpha-hairpinin peptide). IgE binding to the mature vicilin was similar to the that of the full-length protein for all sera.
naSequence: The natural full-length protein is cleaved in vivo into an N-terminal alpha-hairpinin peptide (5.7 kDa) and a C-terminal mature vicilin (45 kDa), which contains the two cupin domains. Signal peptide: 1-24; alpha-hairpinin: 25-70; mature vilcilin: 71-471. Cleavage sites were confirmed by tandem MS of the natural proteins. Glycosylation: the natural mature vilcilin is N-glycosylated at pos. 254 (corresponding to pos. 324 of the full-length sequence).
AminoAcidRef: Thermo Fisher Scientific, Research and Development

Name: Dau c 1

Allergenicity: Sera from 26 of 40 carrot allergic sera were shown to have IgE that bound to recombinant carrot proteins expressed in E. coli:  rDau c 1.0201, 98% bound to rDau c 1.0104 and 20% to rDau c 4 while 20% had IgE to Cross-reactive carbohydrate determinants.  Specificity of binding was high compared to non-allergic controls, but cross-reactivity was noted using birch pollen allergic subjects who do not have carrot allergy, especially for rDau c 1.0104.  However, only 1 of 21 birch pollen only sensitized subjects had demonstrable IgE binding to rDau c 1.0201. Reciprocal inhibition also demonstrated the presence of both shared and unique IgE epitopes.

naSequence: Signal peptide: 1-26, vicilin_N peptides: 27-367, mature vicilin: 368-789. The N-terminal part is cleaved off and cleaved into 6 vicilin_N (alpha-hairpinin) peptides. Both, the N-terminal peptides as well as the mature vicilin were detected in hazelnut extract by MS/MS.

Allergenicity: rPla a 3.0201 showed similar IgE binding capacity as nPla a 3 in experimental ImmunoCAP (r = 0.98). The frequency of sensitization to Pla a 3 was 53% among patients allergic to both plane pollen and peach and 10% among plane pollen allergics tolerating peach. Pla a 3 and Pru p 3 showed strong bidirectional IgE cross-reactivity in patients allergic to peach and plane pollen, but not in peach allergics tolerating plane pollen. Levels of IgE-binding were generally higher to Pru p 3 than to Pla a 3.

Name: Tri t 4
Allergenicity:
The taxonomy of Arthroderma and Trichophyton is a bit messy. [Arthroderma benhamiae (anamorph: Trichophyton mentagrophytes]. Tri m 4, Tri r 4 and Tri t 4 appear to be homologues that are close. These proteins seem to be important in IgE mediated and DTH responses in those with skin or nail fungal infections who are also IgE sensitized and experience immediate responses. Woodfolk has a very good review in 2005, and also specific IgE binding in 1998.


The Woodfolk 1996 article used sera from 30 subjects with SPT + tests to Hollister-Stier's Trichophyton mixture (T. tonsurans, T. rubrum and T. mentagrophytes. They also used individuals with althletes foot. The protein was purified from T. tonsurans, characterized with N-terminal sequencing. It was used as a target for IgE in ELISA and RAST. Six of nine individuals with immediate hypersensitivity had SPT positive responses to Tri t 4 (= Tri m 4).

See also Trichophyton 2, as well as Trichophyton 4 (a different protein, but probably involved in the same reactions.
SubInst: University of Virginia
naSequence: N-terminal amino acid sequence  This sequence matches sequences of four homologous species of Trichophyton, by BLASTP
AminoAcidRef: University of Virginia

Name: Fag e 4
Allergenicity:
Seven serum donors with convincing case histories of buckwheat allergy
were tested. Food challenges were performed with positive outcome in 3/7
patients whereas not done in 4/7. SPTs were performed using total
extract of the source as well as for oral food challenges.
Serum derived IgE to native proteins from the extract was tested by
western blot (6/7 positive). 5/7 samples were positive to purified Fag e
4 in ELISA.
Natural exposure is by ingestion. Controls were performed with sera
from 5 healthy donors, and 28 sera from atopic controls.
SubInst: Medical University of Vienna
naSequence: Sequence of first 12 AA confirmed previously published sequence from Fujimura et al., 2003
AminoAcidRef: Medical University of Vienna

Name: Sal s 6
Allergenicity:
A total of 87 fish-allergic patients were included in this study. All had a convincing history of IgE-mediated fish allergy, and a sensitization to fish confirmed by ImmunoCAP and/or skin prick test with fish extracts. All sera were tested for IgE binding to a pool of barramundi, Atlantic salmon and Yellowfin tuna collagens by ELISA. 19 patients were positive. Of those, 13 sera were then tested in immunoblots to check IgE binding to collagen from specific fish species and for specific collagen alpha chains. 
Of 13 sera tested in immunoblot, IgE from 11 bound to collagen alpha 1 and alpha 2 chains from both muscle and skin tissue of Atlantic salmon. 
In addition, basophil activation test was performed with whole blood of one of the collagen-sensitized patients and one negative control, using salmon muscle collagen as stimulant of basophils. The result was positive for the collagen-sensitized patient and negative for the negative control.
As negative controls, 3 non-atopic individuals without history of type I allergy and 2 atopic individuals with allergies other than fish were used for ELISA and immunoblots. One atopic control was used in basophil activation test.
SubInst: Medical University of Vienna; James Cook University
AminoAcidRef: Medical University of Vienna, Austria; James Cook University

Sequence identification:
The purified collagen fractions from skin and muscle of Atlantic salmon were subjected to SDS-PAGE followed by excision of  bands, tryptic digestion and identification by LC-MS-MS. The upper band (about 140 kDa) was identified as collagen type I alpha 1 chain (with two sequences identified), the lower band (about 130 kDa) as collagen type I alpha 2 chain (also with two sequences identified).

Sequence coverage:
Skin: Sal s 6.0101 29%, Sal s 6.0102 25%, Sal s 6.0201 30%, Sal s 6.0202 32%
Muscle: Sal s 6.0101 21%, Sal s 6.0102 15%, Sal s 6.0201 33%, Sal s 6.0202 28%

In addition, basophil activation test was performed with whole blood of one of the collagen-sensitized patients and one negative control, using salmon muscle collagen as stimulant of basophils. The result was positive for the collagen-sensitized patient and negative for the negative control.
As negative controls, 3 non-atopic individuals without history of type I allergy and 2 atopic individuals with allergies other than fish were used for ELISA and immunoblots. One atopic control was used in basophil activation test.

AminoAcidRef: MacKay Medical College

Name: Ara h 18
Allergenicity: Sera of 15 subjects with suspected peanut allergy who tested positive for IgE to peanut but negative to all peanut components available for routine testing (Ara h 1, 2, 3, 6, 8 and 9), as well as to profilin and CCD, were investigated. Cyclophilin was found to be a dominant cause of positive peanut IgE test results in 13 of these 15 (87%) subjects, with IgE levels to recombinant Ara h 18 comparable or greater than to peanut extract. IgE inhibition experiments performed in five sera using rAra h 18 confirmed the conclusion from the IgE binding resuts. All IgE data were generated using the ImmunoCAP assay platform.
SubInst: Thermo Fisher Scientific R&D

naSequence: The purified natural shrimp hemocyanin was identified by cutting the spot out from a 2D gel and analysing by LC-MS after in-gel trypic digestion. Name: Hum j 6
Allergenicity: Twenty-two patients with respiratory allergy who were sensitized to Japanese hop (specific IgE measured by ImmunoCAP) were tested. Of those, 19 (86%) had IgE to natural Hum j 6 purified from Humulus japonicus pollen as determined by ELISA. In contrast, recombinant allergens produced in E. coli Origami and Pichia pastoris bound only low amounts of IgE from 10 and 11 sera, respectively. The natural allergen is highly phosphorylated, but dephosphorylation did not affect IgE binding, as determined by immunoblot.
SubInst: Yonsei University College of Medicine
naSequence: 15 phosphorylated amino acid residues were detected by tandem-MS of the the purified natural protein
AminoAcidRef: Yonsei University College of Medicine

Name: Pla a 5
Allergenicity: Twenty-three P. acerifolia-sensitized patients with allergic rhinitis in spring were tested. All has positive SPT and sIgE (measured by ImmunoCAP) to plane tree pollen extract. Of those 12 (52%) had serum IgE to recombinant Pla a 5, measured by ELISA. Natural purified Pla a 5 was tested by IgE immunoblot and yielded a positive signal in 4/7 (57%) tested sera. nPla a 5 was also tested by BAT and activated basophils from all three tested Pla a 5-sensitized patients.
SubInst: Jiangsu Cancer Hospital & Jiangsu Institute of Cancer Research & The Affiliated Cancer Hospital of Nanjing Medical University; State Key Laboratory of Complex Severe and Rare Diseases, PUMCH, CAMS
naSequence: Pla a 5 was purified from P. acerifolia pollen extract and identified by tandem MS (71% sequence coverage). The sequence was obtained by NGS of pollen cDNA and amplified by PCR.
AminoAcidRef: Jiangsu Cancer Hospital & Jiangsu Institute of Cancer Research & The Affiliated Cancer Hospital of Nanjing Medical University; State Key Laboratory of Complex Severe and Rare Diseases, PUMCH, CAMS

Name: Pla a 6
Allergenicity: Thirty-seven P. acerifolia-sensitized patients with allergic rhinitis in spring were tested. All has positive SPT and sIgE (measured by ImmunoCAP) to plane tree pollen extract. Name: Art si 14
Allergenicity: n an IgE dot-blot, natural Art si 14 as well as recombinant Art si 14.0101, produced in E. coli, bound IgE from 10 of 20 sera (50%) from Artemisia pollen allergic patients (symptoms: allergic rhinitis and/or asthma; ImmunoCAP class >= 3 with A. vulgaris ImmunoCAP). Nine of the ten dot-blot-positive sera also bound both allergens in IgE Western blot. In an IgE-ELISA, 50 of 87 sera (57%) from Artemisia pollen allergic patients had IgE to rArt si 14.0101. IgE ELISA inhibitions with a pool of Art si 14-sensitized sera showed partial inhibition of IgE binding to A. sieversiana pollen extract by natural and recombinant Art si 14 as well as a high extent of cross-reactivity with Art an 14. In a BAT assay, 3 of 3 Art si 14-sensitized patients reacted with rArt si 14.
SubInst: Jiangsu Cancer Hospital & Jiangsu Institute of Cancer Research & The Affiliated Cancer Hospital of Nanjing Medical University; State Key Laboratory of Complex Severe and Rare Diseases, PUMCH, CAMS
naSequence: Natural Art si 14 was purified from A. sieversiana pollen extract and identified by mass spectrometry. The sequence of rArt si 14.0101 was PCR-amplified from Artemisia sieversiana pollen RNA by using primers based on the sequence obtained from the A. sieversiana transcriptome.
AminoAcidRef: Jiangsu Cancer Hospital & Jiangsu Institute of Cancer Research & The Affiliated Cancer Hospital of Nanjing Medical University; State Key Laboratory of Complex Severe and Rare Diseases, PUMCH, CAMS

Name: Art an 14
Allergenicity: Sera from 20 pollen-allergic patients (allergic rhinitis and/or asthma) sensitized to Artemisia pollen (ImmunoCAP class >= 3 with A. vulgaris ImmunoCAP) were tested. Of those, 9 (45%) had IgE to recombinant Art an 14.0101, produced in E. coli. In a BAT assay with 3 Art an 14-sensitized patients, 2 of 3 reacted with rArt an 14.0101. In an IgE ELISA with a pool of Art an 14-sensitized sera, a high extent of IgE cross-reactivity with Art si 14 was shown.
SubInst: Jiangsu Cancer Hospital & Jiangsu Institute of Cancer Research & The Affiliated Cancer Hospital of Nanjing Medical University; State Key Laboratory of Complex Severe and Rare Diseases, PUMCH, CAMS
naSequence: Art an 14 was identified in A. annua pollen extract by mass spectrometry. The sequence of rArt an 14.0101 was PCR-amplified from Artemisia annua pollen RNA by using primers based on the sequence obtained from the A. annua transcriptome.

Name: Bac s 1
Allergenicity: Eigth patients with IgE-mediated food allergy to natto (soybeans fermented with Bacillus subtilis subsp. natto) were tested. All patients had immediate allergic reactions after ingestion of natto as well as positive SPT with natto. Of these patients, 4/8 (50%) had IgE to a 30 kDa protein from natto as well as from an extract from cultured B. subtilis subsp. natto detected by IgE immunoblot. The protein was identified by immunoblot inhibition with commercially available nattokinase and by mass spectrometry. Moreover, all 4 sera reacted to nattokinase in ELISA. Three patients were also tested with nattokinase by SPT and showed a reaction to the protein. Purity of the purchased nattokinase was confirmed by mass spectrometry.
SubInst: Fujita Health University, Integrative Medical Science for Allergic Disease; Hoyu co. ltd, General Research and Development Institute
AminoAcidRef: Fujita Health University, Integrative Medical Science for Allergic Disease; Hoyu co. ltd, General Research and Development Institute

Name: Hel a 15
Allergenicity: Sera from 30 subjects were tested. Among them, 17 patients were allergic to sunflower seeds (SFS), with SFS-specific IgE > 0.35 kU/L (ImmunoCAP). Serum controls were from 13 patients tolerant to SFS but allergic to other foods. Eleven of 17 (65%) SFS-allergic but none of the 13 SFS-tolerant food-allergic patients had IgE to Hel a 15, as measured by ELISA with the natural purified allergen.
SubInst: French National Research Institute for Agriculture, Food and Environment (INRAE), Universit Paris-Saclay
naSequence: SESA2 encodes a 285 amino acid preproalbumin comprising an signal peptide, a propeptide and two mature 2S albumins connected by a linker peptide. Processing results in two mature 2S albumins, SESA2-1 and SESA2-2, which are both monomeric. SESA2-1 is a mixture of two isoforms differing by the presence or absence of a C-terminal Thr. The allergen was purified from an SFS cold press meal obtained after oil extraction by using ammonium sulfate precipitation, ion exchange chromatography and reversed-phase HPLC as described in Achour et al., 2021 (https://doi.org/10.1002/mnfr.202100369). Sequence confirmed by LC-MS-MS (67% coverage including diagnostic peptides to discriminate between highly similar variants) and by the total mass corresponding to the calculated one.
AminoAcidRef: French National Research Institute for Agriculture, Food and Environment (INRAE), Universit Paris-Saclay
